'''Saccate''' is a term used in botany to describe plant parts that are shaped like a pouch or sack.<ref>{{cite book | last = Harrison | first = Lorraine | authorlink = | title = Latin for Gardeners | publisher = [[Royal Horticultural Society]] | series = | volume = | edition = | date = 2012 | location = | pages = 181 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 9781845337315 | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> Sometimes, when all members of a [[taxon]] share a property of having some part being saccate, this is referred to in the name of the taxon, such as the algae family [[Phaeosaccionaceae]].
